        {
            "heading":"Lectures",
            "items":[
                {
                    "name":"Lecture 1",
                    "contents":[
                        {
                            "type":"label",
                            "text":"ยง1.1 Mathematical Models, Solutions, and Direction Fields"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"What is a differential equation? DE \n\tA relationship between a function (input and output values) and its derivatives."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"The order of a DE is the highest number derivative appearing."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"1) 1st order, linear, non-autonomous ODE"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{dy}{dt}+ty+1=0"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"2) algebraic equation"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"y^2+t^y=0"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"3) 2nd order, non-linear ODE"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"y\\frac{d^2y}{dt^2}+t=0"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"4) linear delay DE"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"f\\prime(t)+t^2-f(t-1)=0"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"5) partial differential equation, multiple independent variables"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{\\partial^2 y}{\\partial x^2}=\\frac{\\partial y}{\\partial t}, y(x,t)"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"A first order ODE has the generic form"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\phi(t,y(t),y\\prime(t))=0"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"Immediate Questions: \n\tIs there such a function y(t)? existence \n\tIs it the only one? uniqueness \n\tHow do you find it? solution approach"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"Countless fundamental laws (all sciences, engineering, economics, finance, etc) are expressed as differential equations."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"eg. Newton's 2nd Law \"Force\""
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{d}{dt}(m \\frac{dy}{dt})=F(t,y,\\frac{dy}{dt})"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":""
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"label",
                            "text":"Direction Fields"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{dy}{dt}=f(t,y)"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"gives the slope of a solution at end point t, y"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"Computer approach: create a table of values, and find solutions what pass through specific points."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"Human approach: Solve for collections of points with a given slope."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":"eg."
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{dy}{dt}=yt"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"math_label",
                            "latex":"\\frac{dy}{dt}=C, y=\\frac{C}{t}"
                        },
                        {
                            "type":"textview",
                            "text":""
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "name":"Lecture 2"
                }
            ]
